<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="0a313320-54cc-5993-93f9-bde47ff9ee3e" activityNameId="b597fbee-660c-4035-8279-785f27a29b10" parentActivityId="f6b99bf9-920e-4b47-a66a-92059050252a" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">polyether polyols production, long chain</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Polyether-Polyol</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">polyether-polyols</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends once  the product, i.e., 1 kg of long chain polyether polyol, is at the production site gate. Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.
</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the average production of 1 kg of long chain polyether polyol (MW &gt; 1000 g/mol). Polyether polyols are polymeric organic compounds including ether groups (R-O-R) and terminal hydroxyl groups (OH). Polyether polyols are one of the precursors of polyurethane (PUR) foam, whille the wide range of properties of PUR foams is largely determined by the used polyols.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Two different classes of polyether polyols can be distinguished, i.e., (1) long-chain polyols (mainly used for producing flexible foams, combined with toluene diisocyanate) and (2) short chain polyols (mainly used for producing rigid foams, combined with methylene diphenyl diisocyanate). Long chain polyether polyols (MW &gt; 1000 kg/kmole) are waxy solids, while short chain ones (MW &lt; 1000 kg/kmole) are liquids.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Polyether polyols are produced by the alkoxylation process with propylene oxide and ethylene oxide being the main raw materials. The production take place in batch mode in the presence of an initiator with an OH functional group (e.g., glycerine, saccharose or other carbohydrates, is commonly used), while a potassium hydroxide (KOH) is used as catalyst. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Adam, N., Avar, G., Blankenheim, H., Friederichs, W., Giersig, M., Weigand, E., Halfmann, M., Wittbecker, F.-W., Larimer, D.-R., Maier, U., Meyer-Ahrens, S., Noble, K.-L. and Wussow, H.-G. (2005). Polyurethanes. In Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, (Ed.). https://doi.org/10.1002/14356007.a21_665.pub2</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">2021, ISOPA , Eco-profile of toluene diisocyanate (TDI) and methylene diphenyl diisocyanate (MDI) , 3 - SeparatePublication</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">2021, ISOPA , Eco-profile of long and short chain polyether polyols for polyurethane products</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">[This dataset is meant to replace the following datasets:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8"> - polyol production, RER, 1995 - 2001 (80d5c197-ffb3-41cf-8d31-ceaeae10e71a)]</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="4a11cbd4-74bf-47fb-9fe5-6e97e3db136b">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2013:Manufacture of plastics and synthetic rubber in primary forms</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0723d252-7e2a-11de-9820-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RER</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Representative for 80 % of the long chain polyether polyols coverage in terms of production volumes in the EU region.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This inventory represents the average production of long chain polyether polyols, provided as a generic dataset. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Polyether polyols are produced by the alkoxylation process, where ethylene oxide and propylene oxide react in the presence of an initiator with an OH functional group (e.g., glycerine, saccharose or other carbohydrates, is commonly used), while a potassium hydroxide (KOH) is used as catalyst. Notably, the amount of alkoxylation species can be varied to achieve different chain lengths and molecular weights.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">In more detail, the process takes place in a batch mode, where an initiator and a base (catalyst) are first introduced. The role of the initiator and the catalyst is generate an alcoholate-anion, subsequently the epoxide is introduced and the reaction operates at approximately 100 - 130 °C at a pressure within the following range 2 - 5 bar. The reaction is strongly exothermic, and thus, the cooling of the reactor is important to maintain the temperature level within the latter range.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Finally, the long chain polyether polyol product has to be purified i.e. separated from the spent catalyst, which takes place through the introduction of an acid which reacts with the base (i.e., catalyst) to form an insoluble salt which is easily removed by filtering.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">2021, ISOPA , Eco-profile of long and short chain polyether polyols for polyurethane products</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2020-01-01" endDate="2026-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Data collection for production was collected as 12-month averages representing the year 2018. The inventory creation and calculation stage was concluded in 2020, while the technology is not expected to change until 2026.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
